YENAGOA – The Bayelsa State Governor, Douye Diri, has described the death of the late Prof. Nimisoere Briggs as a huge loss to Nigeria and the Ijaw nation in particular. According to him, the late scholar was an academic Iroko whose passing has created a yawning gap in the pantheon of the Ijaw ethnic group and Nigeria’s academic greats. Prof. Briggs died on Monday at the age of 79. He was Emeritus Professor of Medicine, former Vice-Chancellor, University of Port Harcourt, Pro-Chancellor, Federal University, Abakaliki and the Bayelsa Medical University as well as Chairman, the Committee of Pro-Chancellors of Nigerian Universities. Diri, in a statement issued by his Chief Press Secretary, Daniel Alabrah, on Wednesday, said the Kalabari-born academic, who hails from Abonnema in Rivers State, impacted and inspired a generation and countless others with his outstanding record of achievements. The governor commiserated with his family, the Kalabari people and the academic community. He noted that Prof. Briggs’ wise counsel, candour, dedication and commitment to the service of Nigeria and humanity would be greatly missed.‒‒:‒‒/‒‒:‒‒ Diri said, “The news of Prof. Briggs death was shocking and sad. The Ijaw nation and indeed Nigeria has lost an intellectual giant and academic Iroko. POLL “Prof. Briggs served our country and the academic community with commendable dedication and commitment. His wise counsel and candour were the hallmarks of a man of service. We will all miss his humility and affable nature.” The governor, on behalf of the government and people of Bayelsa State, prayed God to comfort the family and grant them the grace to bear the loss.